description:
## Severity
Major
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/oauth.rs:528-575 (persist_to_disk)
## Violation
```rust
let tmp_path = path.with_extension("tmp");
if let Err(e) = fs::write(&tmp_path, &json) { ... }
if let Err(e) = fs::rename(&tmp_path, path) { ... }
...
#[cfg(unix)]
{
    use std::os::unix::fs::PermissionsExt;
    if let Ok(metadata) = fs::metadata(path) {
        let mut perms = metadata.permissions();
        perms.set_mode(0o600);
        ...
    }
}
```

`fs::write` creates `<path>.tmp` with the process umask — typically `0o644` for users with default `umask 022`, or `0o664` for `umask 002`. The OAuth refresh+access tokens land on disk world-readable for the brief window between `fs::write` and `fs::rename`, and then for a second window between `rename` and the chmod-to-0600 call. Concurrent `cat` or `inotify`-watching processes on the same host can race the read.

The rename also preserves the tmp file's permissions on the destination, NOT the original file's permissions — so on a system where the destination was previously 0600, the rename CLOBBERS the secure mode and replaces it with 0644 until the explicit chmod runs.

Additionally `fs::write(&tmp_path, ...)` will TRUNCATE an existing `.tmp` file with no exclusive-create check; a malicious local user can pre-create the tmp file as a symlink to `/etc/shadow` or any other path and the rename target leaks. (The destination `path` itself has a symlink-defense in `load_from_disk`, but the `.tmp` step has none.)
## Mandated refactor
Use `OpenOptions::new().create_new(true).write(true).mode(0o600).open(tmp)` (requires `std::os::unix::fs::OpenOptionsExt`) to atomically create the tmp file with exclusive mode and final permissions in a single syscall. Reject `.tmp` if it already exists. Add a `fs::remove_file(&tmp_path)` guard on every error path so a half-written tmp doesn't survive across runs. On non-Unix, document the absence of secure permissions and refuse to persist credentials at all.
